    pearls: ["The Beers Criteria is updated every 3-4 years by the AGS; the NP must stay current with the latest edition as medications are added and removed based on new evidence","Anticholinergic burden is cumulative: individually low-risk medications can produce significant anticholinergic toxicity when combined (e.g., oxybutynin + diphenhydramine + meclizine)","Proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) are listed as use with caution beyond 8 weeks due to increased risk of C. difficile infection, fractures, and hypomagnesemia in older adults","NSAIDs are Beers-listed due to increased GI bleeding, renal injury, and cardiovascular risk; the risk is amplified when combined with anticoagulants, corticosteroids, or antiplatelet agents","Benzodiazepines of any duration are Beers-listed due to cognitive impairment, delirium, falls, fractures, and motor vehicle accidents in older adults; if already prescribed chronically, taper slowly (reduce by 10-25% every 2-4 weeks)","Sliding-scale insulin as the sole glucose management is Beers-listed because it causes reactive glycemic swings without addressing basal insulin needs","The STOPP/START criteria complement Beers by also identifying medications that SHOULD be started (e.g., bisphosphonates for osteoporosis, statins for secondary prevention) in addition to those to stop"],
