    pearls: ["Safety is the number one nursing priority in bipolar disorder: suicide risk is highest during mixed episodes (energy of mania + hopelessness of depression) and depressive episodes","Decreased sleep need is often the earliest warning sign of an impending manic episode — teach patients and families to report this immediately; it differs from insomnia (patient feels rested on little sleep vs wanting to sleep but unable)","Lithium has the strongest evidence for suicide prevention among all mood stabilizers — this is a key reason to select lithium despite its monitoring requirements","Never give antidepressant monotherapy to a bipolar patient: SSRIs/SNRIs without a mood stabilizer can trigger mania, mixed episodes, or rapid cycling","Medication nonadherence is the most common cause of relapse: patients may feel well and stop medications, or miss the elevated mood of hypomania; consistent education and therapeutic alliance are essential","During acute mania, provide low-stimulation environment: private room if possible, dim lights, minimize noise, reduce visitors; excessive stimulation worsens manic symptoms","Monitor metabolic parameters for patients on atypical antipsychotics: fasting glucose, lipid panel, weight, waist circumference at baseline, 3 months, then annually (metabolic syndrome risk)"],
